Chloride-mediated inhibition for suppression of prediction\n- No mention of GABAergic inhibition\n- Score: null\n\n**4. Habituation to Sequence** - Habituation suppresses local oddball response relative to a novel local oddball\n- The study shows that feedback mismatch responses became smaller the longer the animal was exposed to open-loop condition (Figure 3B)\n\n\n- This demonstrates habituation to the mismatch signal\n- Score: +0.6 (moderate evidence)\n\n**5. Synaptic Depression (Adaptation)** - Passive fatigue of synaptic efficacy due to repetition\n- The study doesn\'t specifically address synaptic depression mechanisms\n- Score: null\n\n**6. Activity Suppression** - Reduction in firing rates for expected (predictable) stimuli\n- The study shows that visual input alone is a poor predictor of activity, and that mismatch responses are stronger than expected\n- However, they don\'t directly show suppression of expected stimuli\n- Score: null\n\n**7. Selective Sharpening** - Signal-to-noise increase for predictable stimuli\n- Not addressed in the study\n- Score: null\n\n**8. Alpha/Beta Mediated Suppression** - Desynchronization in low-frequency bands\n- The study uses calcium imaging, not LFP/EEG, so no frequency analysis\n- Score: null\n\n**9. VIP-Mediated Disinhibition** - VIP-mediated inhibition of SST/PV neurons\n- Not addressed\n- Score: null\n\n**10. Precision Weighting (Gain)** - Top-down amplification of error units\n- The study discusses predictive coding but doesn\'t specifically address precision weighting\n- Score: null\n\n**11. E/I Balance Shift** - Dynamic adjustment toward higher inhibition for predictable stimuli\n- Not addressed\n- Score: null\n\n**12. Omission Response** - Top-down generated internal signal in absence of prediction-mediated suppression\n- The study shows responses to feedback mismatch (when visual flow is halted during running)\n- This could be considered an omission response - the expected visual flow is omitted\n- Score: +0.6 (moderate evidence)\n\n## H2: Feedforward Error Propagation (IDs 13-24)\n\n**13. Feedforward Deviance Detection** - Detection of mismatch signals that explicitly propagate feedforward\n- The study shows mismatch detection in V1, but doesn\'t explicitly show feedforward propagation\n- Score: null\n\n**14. Feedforward AMPA** - Fast excitatory drive mediated by AMPA receptors\n- Not addressed\n- Score: null\n\n**15. Feedforward NMDA** - Voltage-dependent amplification of error signals\n- Not addressed\n- Score: null\n\n**16. Feedforward Ascending Gamma** - Rhythmic synchronization (30-90Hz)\n- Not addressed (calcium imaging, no gamma analysis)\n- Score: null\n\n**17. Feedforward Specific Error** - Functional requirement that error signal must be strictly feedforward-directed\n- Not addressed\n- Score: null\n\n**18. Supragranular Activity (L2/3)** - Localization of error-signaling neurons in Layers 2/3\n- The study explicitly records from layer 2/3 and shows mismatch responses there\n- Score: +0.8 (strong evidence)\n\n**19. Granular Activity (L4)** - Arrival of prediction error signals in Layer 4\n- The study doesn\'t record from L4\n- Score: null\n\n**20. Feedforward Directed Connectivity** - Directional measures confirming feedforward propagation\n- Not addressed\n- Score: null\n\n**21. Feedforward Activation** - Functional activation patterns tracing feedforward propagation\n- Not addressed\n- Score: null\n\n**22. Ascending Latency Shift** - Systematic increases in response latency characterizing feedforward propagation\n- Not addressed\n- Score: null\n\n**23. Feedforward Error Propagation** - Explicit experimental evidence that error signal is transmitted via feedforward pathways\n- The study discusses predictive coding but doesn\'t provide explicit evidence of feedforward propagation\n- Score: null\n\n**24. Subcortical Feedforward Relaying** - Relaying of prediction error by subcortical structures\n- Not addressed\n- Score: null\n\n## H3: Ubiquity (IDs 25-36)\n\n**25