epeated stimuli. Figure 7 shows stimulus response decay (adaptation) while omission responses stay constant. This supports habituation. → +0.6 (moderate evidence - adaptation shown in Fig 7)\n\n**5. Synaptic Depression (Adaptation)** - The study discusses adaptation effects (Fig 7A shows fast decay of stimulus response). They mention "adaptation effect to the repeated stimuli" (p.4). → +0.6 (moderate evidence)\n\n\n**6. Activity Suppression** - The study demonstrates reduced firing rates for predictable stimuli through adaptation, with omission responses revealing the underlying prediction signal. → +0.6 (moderate evidence)\n\n**7. Selective Sharpening** - No direct measurement of signal-to-noise ratio changes. → null\n\n**8. Alpha/Beta Mediated Suppression** - The study doesn\'t investigate low-frequency band desynchronization. → null\n\n**9. VIP-Mediated Disinhibition** - No specific investigation of VIP-mediated mechanisms. → null\n\n**10. Precision Weighting (Gain)** - The study explores how brain state modulates omission responses, suggesting potential gain modulation, though not explicitly framed as precision weighting. → +0.2 (weak evidence)\n\n**11. E/I Balance Shift** - No direct measurement of excitation-inhibition balance dynamics. → null\n\n**12. Omission Response** - The study\'s central finding demonstrates robust neural activity during stimulus omission, providing strong evidence for this mechanism. → +1.0 (strong evidence)\n\n## H2: Feedforward Error Propagation (IDs 13-24)\n\n**13. Feedforward Deviance Detection** - The study identifies omission responses as potential prediction error signals, though feedforward propagation isn\'t directly demonstrated. → +0.2 (weak evidence)\n\n**14. Feedforward AMPA** - No specific investigation of AMPA receptor-mediated feedforward transmission. → null\n\n**15. Feedforward NMDA** - No direct measurement of NMDA receptor involvement in feedforward error signaling. → null\n\n**16. Feedforward Ascending Gamma** - The study doesn\'t examine gamma-band synchronization for feedforward transmission. → null\n\n**17. Feedforward Specific Error** - While the study discusses prediction error, it doesn\'t explicitly characterize the feedforward nature of these signals. → null\n\n**18. Supragranular Activity (L2/3)** - The study maps omission-sensitive neurons across cortical layers, including supragranular regions, though without explicitly linking this to feedforward error propagation. → +0.2 (weak evidence)\n\n**19. Granular Activity (L4)** - Omission-sensitive neurons are present in granular layers, but the study doesn\'t frame this as feedforward error signal arrival. → +0.2 (weak evidence)\n\n**20. Feedforward Directed Connectivity** - The study lacks directional connectivity analysis (Granger causality, transfer entropy) to establish feedforward propagation. → null\n\n**21. Feedforward Activation** - No functional imaging or activation tracing to demonstrate feedforward signal propagation. → null\n\n**22. Ascending Latency Shift** - The study measures response latencies but doesn\'t systematically track latency increases across hierarchical levels. → null\n\n**23. Feedforward Error Propagation** - The study discusses prediction error signals but doesn\'t provide explicit evidence for their feedforward transmission through cortical layers. → null\n\n**24. Subcortical Feedforward Relaying** - The study identifies omission responses in the inferior colliculus, suggesting subcortical involvement in error signaling, though feedforward relaying isn\'t directly demonstrated. → +0.2 (weak evidence)\n\n## H3: Ubiquity (IDs 25-36)\n\n**25. Canonical Microcircuit Ubiquity** - The study discusses canonical microcircuit formulations but doesn\'t provide evidence for their ubiquitous presence across cortical levels. → null\n\n**26. Hierarchical Mechanism Invariance** - The study doesn\'t systematically compare predictive coding mechanisms across different hierarchical levels. → null\n\n**27. Hierarchical Activity Ubiquity** - The study finds omission responses across multiple auditory areas (IC, AC), suggesting widespread prediction error activity, though not comprehively across all hierarchical levels. → +0.6 (moderate evidence)\n\n**28. Hierarchical CSD Ubiquity** - The study doesn\'t perform current source density analysis across hierarchical levels. → null\n\n**29. Cross-Scale Hierarchical Ubiquity** - The study uses single-unit recordings but doesn\'t systematically compare across multiple scales (single units to LFP). → null\n\n**30. Hierarchical Presence (V1-PFC)** - The study focuses on auditory areas (IC, AC) rather than visual or prefrontal regions. → null\n\n**31. Cross-Modal Ubiquity** - The study is limited to auditory modality, not examining multiple sensory modalities. → null\n\n**32. Interspecies Hierarchical Ubiquity** - The study compares rats and mice, finding similar omission responses across species, suggesting conserved hierarchical mechanisms. → +0.6 (moderate evidence)\n\n**33. Temporal Stability of Ubiquity** - The study doesn\'t explicitly assess temporal stability across extended recording sessions. → null\n\n**34. Hierarchical Order Stability** - The study doesn\'t systematically evaluate hierarchical order stability. → null\n\n**35. Population-Wide Ubiquity** - The study finds omission-sensitive neurons across different populations, though not comprehively across all cell types. → +0.2 (weak evidence)\n\n**36. State-Independent Ubiquity** - The study demonstrates omission responses persist across brain states (anesthetized and awake), suggesting state-independent mechanisms. → +0.6 (moderate evidence)\n\nI\'m noticing the study provides moderate evidence for hierarchical and interspecies conservation of predictive coding mechanisms, with some weak evidence for population-wide and state-independent properties. However, several key aspects remain unexplored, particularly around canonical microcircuit ubiquity, cross-modal compa