 or adaptation\n- Score: null\n\n**6. Activity Suppression** - Reduction in firing rates for expected (predictable) stimuli\n- The study discusses prediction errors but doesn't explicitly measure activity suppression for expected stimuli\n- Score: null\n\n**7. Selective Sharpening** - Signal-to-noise increase for predictable stimuli\n- The study discusses noise suppression (Fig. 5) but not selective sharpening per se\n\n\n- Score: null\n\n**8. Alpha/Beta Mediated Suppression** - Desynchronization in low-frequency bands\n- The study doesn't discuss alpha/beta oscillations\n- Score: null\n\n**9. VIP-Mediated Disinhibition** - VIP-mediated inhibition of SST/PV neurons\n- The study doesn't discuss VIP neurons\n- Score: null\n\n**10. Precision Weighting (Gain)** - Top-down amplification of error units\n- The study discusses top-down context but not precision weighting or gain modulation\n- Score: null\n\n**11. E/I Balance Shift** - Dynamic adjustment toward higher inhibition for predictable stimuli\n- The study doesn't discuss E/I balance shifts\n- Score: null\n\n**12. Omission Response** - Top-down generated internal signal in absence of prediction-mediated suppression\n- The study discusses prediction errors but not omission responses\n- Score: null\n\n## H2: Feedforward Error Propagation (IDs 13-24)\n\n**13. Feedforward Deviance Detection** - Detection of mismatch signals propagating feedforward\n- The study discusses mismatch errors but they are computed locally, not explicitly propagated feedforward\n- Score: null\n\n**14. Feedforward AMPA** - Fast excitatory drive via AMPA receptors conveying prediction-error\n- The study doesn't discuss AMPA receptors\n- Score: null\n\n**15. Feedforward NMDA** - Voltage-dependent amplification of error signals\n- The study doesn't discuss NMDA receptors\n- Score: null\n\n**16. Feedforward Ascending Gamma** - Rhythmic synchronization (30-90Hz) packaging error signals\n- The study doesn't discuss gamma oscillations\n- Score: null\n\n**17. Feedforward Specific Error** - Functional requirement that error signal must be strictly feedforward-directed\n- The study discusses error signals but they are used for learning, not specifically feedforward propagation\n- Score: null\n\n**18. Supragranular Activity (L2/3)** - Localization of error-signaling neurons in L2/3\n- The study discusses L2/3 as generating predictions, not specifically as error-signaling neurons\n- Score: null\n\n**19. Granular Activity (L4)** - Arrival of prediction error signals in L4\n- The study discusses L4 as receiving thalamic input, not as receiving prediction error signals\n- Score: null\n\n**20. Feedforward Directed Connectivity** - Directional measures confirming feedforward propagation\n- The study doesn't use Granger Causality or Transfer Entropy\n- Score: null\n\n**21. Feedforward Activation** - Functional activation patterns tracing feedforward propagation\n- The study discusses feedforward connections but not specifically for error propagation\n- Score: null\n\n**22. Ascending Latency Shift** - Systematic increases in response latency characterizing feedforward propagation\n- The study discusses temporal delays but not ascending latency shifts\n- Score: null\n\n**23. Feedforward Error Propagation** - Explicit evidence that error signal is transmitted via feedforward pathways\n- The study discusses error signals but they are used for learning, not specifically feedforward propagation\n- Score: null\n\n**24. Subcortical Feedforward Relaying** - Relaying of prediction error by subcortical structures\n- The study discusses thalamic input but not specifically for error relaying\n- Score: null\n\n## H3: Ubiquity (IDs 25-36)\n\n**25. Canonical Microcircuit Ubiquity** - Ubiquitous presence of L2/3 Error and L5/6 Prediction motif\n- The study discusses a canonical microcircuit but doesn't claim ubiquity across hierarchy\n- Score: null\n\n**26. Hierarchical Mechanism Invariance** - Ubiquitous nature of mechanism functioning identically from V1 to PFC\n- The study discusses a single cortical column, not multiple hierarchical levels\n- Score: null\n\n**27. Hierarchical Activity Ubiquity** - Ubiquitous presence of prediction-error activity across hierarchy\n- The study discusses prediction errors but only in a single column\n- Score: null\n\n**28. Hierarchical CSD Ubiquity** - Ubiquity of current source density profiles across hierarchy\n- The study doesn't discuss CSD profiles\n- Score: null\n\n**29. Cross-Scale Hierarchical Ubiquity** - Ubiquity of effects across scales (single units to LFP)\n- The study is computational, doesn't address multiple scales\n- Score: null\n\n**30. Hierarchical Presence (V1-PFC)** - Ubiquity across V1, V4, PFC\n- The study discusses a single cortical column, not multiple areas\n- Score: null\n\n**31. Cross-Modal Ubiquity** - Presence across multiple sensory modalities\n- The study uses visual (Gabor) and sensorimotor tasks but doesn't claim cross-modal ubiquity\n- Score: null\n\n**32. Interspecies Hierarchical Ubiquity** - Conservation across species\n- The study mentions mouse experiments but doesn't compare species\n- Score: null\n\n**33. Temporal Stability of Ubiquity** - Consistent presence across long recording sessions\n- The study doesn't address temporal stability\n- Score: null\n\n**34. Hierarchical Order Stability** - Evidence that mechanism is ubiquitous and not localized to single pole\n- The study doesn't address hierarchical order stability\n- Score: null\n\n**35. Population-Wide Ubiquity** - Consistency across diverse neural populations\n- The study discusses L2/3 and L5 populations but doesn't claim population-wide ubiquity\n- Score: null\n\n**36. State-Independent Ubiquity** - Presence across different brain states\n- The study doesn't address different brain states\n- Score: null\n\nI'm noticing a pattern of null scores across most factors. The study's computational nature and single-column focus limit its ability to address broader hierarchic