tuation to Sequence** - This is about habituation suppressing local oddball response. The paper doesn\'t address habituation or sequence learning in this sense.\n- LO: null\n- GO: null\n\n**5. Synaptic Depression (Adaptation)** - The paper doesn\'t address synaptic depression or adaptation mechanisms.\n\n\n- LO: null\n- GO: null\n\n**6. Activity Suppression** - The model demonstrates how expected inputs get suppressed through interneuron cancellation, reducing apical dendritic activity when predictions match.\n- LO: 0.6\n- GO: 0.6\n\n**7. Selective Sharpening** - The paper doesn\'t explicitly address signal-to-noise ratio improvements or selective noise suppression.\n- LO: null\n- GO: null\n\n**8. Alpha/Beta Mediated Suppression** - No discussion of low-frequency band desynchronization or alpha/beta mechanisms.\n- LO: null\n- GO: null\n\n**9. VIP-Mediated Disinhibition** - The model doesn\'t incorporate VIP neurons or disinhibition pathways.\n- LO: null\n- GO: null\n\n**10. Precision Weighting (Gain)** - While the paper discusses error encoding and learning, it doesn\'t explicitly address precision weighting or gain modulation mechanisms.\n- LO: null\n- GO: null\n\n**11. E/I Balance Shift** - The paper references E/I balance in relation to PV cells but doesn\'t implement this mechanism in the model.\n- LO: null\n- GO: null\n\n**12. Omission Response** - The model doesn\'t address omission responses or top-down generated internal signals.\n- LO: null\n- GO: null\n\n## H2: Feedforward Error Propagation (IDs 13--24)\n\n**13. Feedforward Deviance Detection** - The paper focuses on backpropagation of errors, not feedforward deviance detection.\n- LO: null\n- GO: null\n\n**14. Feedforward AMPA** - The paper doesn\'t address AMPA receptors or feedforward AMPA mechanisms.\n- LO: null\n- GO: null\n\n**15. Feedforward NMDA** - The paper doesn\'t address NMDA receptors or feedforward NMDA mechanisms.\n- LO: null\n- GO: null\n\n**16. Feedforward Ascending Gamma** - The paper do